     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _M_o_r_e acts as a filter that allows text to be viewed one
          screen at a time.  By default, _m_o_r_e pauses when the screen
          has been filled with text. _M_o_r_e then displays the "--More--"
          command prompt at the bottom of the screen.  If the user
          presses <<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>>, another page (screen full) of text is
          displayed.  Pressing <<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>> causes the next line of text to
          be displayed.  The number of lines of text displayed when
          these keys are pressed is adjustable.  There are numerous
          other commands available at the --More-- prompt, and these
          are described below.

          _M_o_r_e can accept multiple files at once.  When a _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c is
          specified, all files that match the _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c will be
          displayed.  If a _d_r_i_v_e_s_p_e_c is specified, only files on that
          particular drive or drives will be displayed.  If the
          _d_r_i_v_e_s_p_e_c and _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c are both omitted, _m_o_r_e will read data
          from standard-in device (normally the keyboard) and displays
          the data that is read.  The output of _m_o_r_e can also be
          redirected out to a device or a file.

          _M_o_r_e accepts several options.  Options are usually specified
          by single characters, and they may be entered in upper or
          lowercase.  Options are always preceded by a hyphen (a "-").
          If you are specifying multiple options, you can specify the
          options in any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----cccc   Each page of text is displayed by starting at the top
               of the screen and erasing the old text on each line
               just before new text is placed on that line.  By
               default, _m_o_r_e scrolls the text from the previous page
               up so that it disappears off the top of the screen, and
               the new text is added at the bottom.


          ----dddd   The --More-- prompt will also display brief a help
               message each time it is displayed.  This is useful with
               users who are unfamiliar with _m_o_r_e.  Note that "?" can
               be pressed at the --More-- prompt to receive help at
               all times.




