          ++++_l_i_n_e_n_u_m_b_e_r
               When specified, _m_o_r_e skips this many lines in the first
               file specified before it begins to display the file
               contents.


          ++++////_p_a_t_t_e_r_n
               When specified, _m_o_r_e will search through the first file
               that is specified looking for the pattern.  When the
               pattern is found, _m_o_r_e will begin displaying the file
               at that point.  _M_o_r_e displays up to four lines in front
               of the point where the match occurs to provide some
               context.

               If the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n is not found, the message """"PPPPaaaatttttttteeeerrrrnnnn nnnnooootttt
               ffffoooouuuunnnndddd"""" is displayed.  If a filename was specified to
               _m_o_r_e, _m_o_r_e repositions to the beginning of the current
               file after the search fails.  If _m_o_r_e was reading from
               the standard input or from a redirected file, _m_o_r_e
               remains positioned at the end of the file.

               _P_a_t_t_e_r_n_s may include all types of wildcards.  Wildcards
               are discussed in the _w_i_l_d_s_p_e_c documentation, below.
               You may also place an uparrow (^) at the start of the
               _p_a_t_t_e_r_n.  The uparrow means that the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n must match
               text at the start of lines in the file.  For example,
               if the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n was "^ine":
                     This line would not match the pattern,
                     ine But this line would.

               By default, the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n will match text anywhere in a
               line.

               The _p_a_t_t_e_r_n is case-sensitive, so upper and lowercase
               characters must match the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n exactly.  The _p_a_t_t_e_r_n
               can specify upper or lowercase for certain characters
               if needed by using _r_a_n_g_e_s.

               Multiple _p_a_t_t_e_r_n_s can also be specified by placing
               <CLEAR><SPACE> character between each _p_a_t_t_e_r_n.  For
               example the _p_a_t_t_e_r_n ABC<CLEAR><SPACE>xyz  would locate
               any occurrence of the sequence "ABC" or the sequence
               "xyz".






