               When the --More-- prompt is displayed, numerous
               commands can be specified.  These allow you to skip to
               the next file, skip further down the current file, even
               search for a particular string within the file.  With
               the exception of the "/" command, no characters are
               echoed while the command is being entered.

               Some of the commands optionally accept a decimal value
               _i.


          [_i]<<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>>
               When the <<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>> key is pressed, another screen worth
               of information is displayed.  By default, 22 new lines
               are displayed each time so that one line from the
               previous screen will remain in the screen.  If a
               decimal value is specified, it will set the number of
               lines that are displayed each time the <<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>> key is
               pressed from now on.


          [_i]<<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>>
               This command causes one more line of the file to be
               displayed.  If a number is specified, it changes the
               number of lines the <<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>> key displays.  The command
               7777<<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>> causes the <<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>> to display seven more lines
               each time it is pressed.


          [_i]<<<<CCCCTTTTRRRRLLLL----DDDD>>>>
               Similar to the <<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>> key, except that 11 more lines
               are displayed.  This default can be changed by
